text: Something just occurred to me. Sure, we lose the horror and atmosphere of the first 2 games, but think about it. Isaac has been the protag of all 3 games. By game 3, he's been in this situation as much as the player. He's come to terms with it. He expects half of what he sees when he sees it begin. I'm not saying he likes it or that he's ok with it, but by then he'd be just as jaded as anyone else who went through hell and came back, like someone serving their third tour in WW1. At this point he'd be going for the arms and legs as a matter of course, mowing down the undead like we do in left for dead. So from his point of view, it's not scary anymore. He knows what's at stake and he's got a job to do, so the stoic bastard picks up his faithful old plasma cutter and heads off to work.
